observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding cash advances, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strengthen the internal control on the grant and liquidation of cash advances by complying with the provisions under Section Nos. 4 and 5 of the COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within the reglementary period;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances; and
Verify the collectability of unliquidated cash advances of more than 10 years, otherwise, request the authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the LGU officials and employees to submit promptly their claims together with complete relevant supporting documents to the Office of the Municipal Accountant;
Hire additional competent personnel in the Accounting Office to facilitate the voluminous transactions occurring each month in the Municipality, and to hasten the process of submission of the necessary accounts to the Office of the Auditor;
Evaluate the process of preparing the disbursement vouchers, RCIs, RCDs, RAAFs, and relevant documents to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years and be reminded that processing of vouchers must only be undertaken when they were properly approved and with complete documentation; and
Remind the concerned officials and employees of the administrative or criminal liability, under Section 39 (1) (3) of PD No. 1445 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code, as amended by Section 41 of RA No. 10951, which may be imposed as a consequence of their inability or refusal to render accounts without justifiable cause.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Supply Officer to conduct pre-repair evaluation/inspection and post-repair evaluation/inspection of all its government vehicles subjected to repairs;
Require that the Report of Waste Material be prepared by the Supply Officer and approved by the Local Chief Executive;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a ledger card for the expenses incurred regarding repair and maintenance of every vehicle owned by the Agency to monitor whether the property is economically repairable; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to always ensure that future payments are properly taken up and recorded in the books in its appropriate accounts.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require that an actual inventory-taking of all assets or PPEs of the LGU be conducted each year pursuant to Section 124, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGUs; that the relevant RPCPPE be submitted not later than January 31 of each year to the Office of the Auditor; and that the same be reconciled with the records of the Municipal Accountant; 

Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and PPELC, respectively, for all the Agency’s PPEs;

Consider creating a GSO who will discharge on a full-time basis the procurement and issuance of supplies and property, maintain updated Property Cards per category on all Agency’s assets as recorded in the list of PPEs of accounting records, and facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCPPE; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries to transfer the PPEs enumerated above to their appropriate accounts and remind her to carefully analyze every transaction before recording them in the Agency’s books.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Make representations with the DBP for reconciliation of their records and obtain copies of debit memos and other related loan documents as reference in adjusting the books to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;

Strengthen accounting controls over loans payable by reviewing thoroughly the amortization schedule given by the bank and carefully analyzing transaction before recording in the books and updating entries of both records; 

Reclassify the current portion of the Loans Payable – Domestic account amounting to ₱4.56 million to its proper classification in the Statement of Financial Position; and

Disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the details of the Loans Payable – Domestic pursuant to Paragraph 127 of IPSAS No. 1.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer, as the Property/ Supply Officer, and the Municipal Accountant to monitor the movement of stocks thru the use and maintenance of RIS and stock cards/stock ledger cards;

Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the required documentary requirements supporting all purchases especially for drugs and medicines are present;

Direct the requesting officers on the procurement of medicines to review the provisions of EO No. 49, s. 1993 and ensure the Agency’s compliance on them, as such, a certification signed by the requesting officer that the drug products being requisitioned conform with PNDF Volume I is required to support the procurement; and

Require the department heads to prepare PPMP, for the procurement of all supplies and materials that their office/s will be needing within the CY, and submit them to the BAC for consolidation. Be reminded that an APP must include all procurement activities planned for the year, not just for office supplies, and only those projects/procurement included therein will be undertaken within the year.

We recommended that Management:

Submit a satisfactory explanation as to the appropriateness and reasonableness of the above-noted observations in the grant of financial assistance;

Regulate the grant of financial assistance to the most essential only and ensure that funds disbursed are property utilized for public welfare and refrain from giving financial assistance which does not conform with the exigencies of the service;

Provide specific guidelines or basis for the rates of the financial assistance given to LGU employees and barangay officials and employees; and

Ensure that future claims be supported with complete documentation.
